21/01/2004
ANKARA, Turkey -- The finance ministry has barred 105,000 people from leaving the country because they each owe more than 9,000 euros in back taxes. The local media reported Tuesday (20 January) that the ban would be extended to another 150,000 taxpayers this year. Only those who do not owe taxes would be issued new passports.
In other news, Iraqi State Oil Marketing Organisation chief Shamkhi Faraj visits Ankara on Wednesday to discuss Turkey's possible participation in rebuilding Iraq's oil industry. It was also announced that a delegation from Baghdad would attend an energy forum in Turkey later this month.
Pakistani President Pervez Musharraf is on an official visit to Ankara, where he met Tuesday with Turkish counterpart Ahmet Necdet Sezer. They discussed bilateral co-operation in the fight against terrorism and organised crime, as well as strengthening economic relations and increasing trade.
Meanwhile, Turkish State Minister Ali Babacan is in Davos, Switzerland to attend the World Economic Forum. He will hold bilateral meetings with IMF First Deputy Managing Director Anne Krueger and a number of government officials and representatives of multinational companies participating in the forum. (Anadolu Agency, NTV, TRT 2 - 21/01/04; AFP, Dow Jones, Anadolu Agency, TRT 2, NTV - 20/01/04)
